      <h1 id="main-heading">Pride and Prejudice</h1>
      <section class="main-section" id="Introduction">
        <header class="headings">
          Introduction
        </header>
        <p id="para">"Pride and Prejudice," authored by Jane Austen and first published in 1813, is a novel centered around the evolution of Elizabeth Bennet. The narrative explores the consequences of hastiness in judgment and emphasizes the distinction between surface-level virtue and genuine goodness.</p>
        <p id="para"> Over the years, "Pride and Prejudice" has consistently ranked high on lists of beloved literary works, capturing the admiration of both scholars and the general readership. It has achieved widespread acclaim in English literature, boasting over 20 million copies sold and serving as a wellspring of inspiration for numerous modern literary creations. The enduring popularity of the novel is evident through its numerous dramatic adaptations, reprints, unofficial sequels, films, and TV renditions, all of which have brought the novel's memorable characters and themes to diverse audiences for more than a century. </p>
      </section>
      <section class="main-section" id="Plot_Summary">
        <header class="headings">
          Plot Summary
        </header>
        <p id="para"> In 19th-century Hertfordshire, Mrs. Bennet strives to secure advantageous marriages for her five daughters. The arrival of wealthy Mr. Bingley raises hopes, but his friend Mr. Darcy's aloofness offends Elizabeth. Misunderstandings unfold, leading to Jane's heartbreak and Elizabeth rejecting Mr. Collins.</p>
        <p id="para">In Kent, revelations about Darcy's interventions and a rejected proposal deepen Elizabeth's animosity. Later, during a tour, she witnesses Darcy's changed behavior at Pemberley. News of Lydia's elopement and Darcy's discreet intervention ensue.</p>
        <p id="para">Despite Lady Catherine's opposition, Darcy proposes again, and this time, Elizabeth accepts. The tale concludes with Jane and Bingley's reunion, and Elizabeth's journey from prejudice to acceptance of Mr. Darcy's love.</p>
      </section>
      <section class="main-section" id="Main_Characters">
